{
  "response_text": "The data from the repeated simulations of the agent-based model show distinct trends in the number of households engaging in social learning over the 100 time steps. Initially, all simulations start with zero households engaging in social learning. By around the 10th time step, there is a noticeable divergence in the number of households adopting social learning behaviors across different simulations. Some simulations show a rapid increase, reaching up to approximately 24 households by the 20th time step, while others exhibit a more gradual adoption rate. By the 30th time step, the number of households engaging in social learning in most simulations stabilizes, with values ranging between 12 and 54 households. Notably, a significant proportion of the simulations show a clustering of households engaging in social learning around the 18 to 24 household mark, while a few simulations depict higher adoption rates, reaching up to 54 households. Beyond the 40th time step, the trends largely plateau, indicating that the number of households adopting social learning behaviors stabilizes and remains constant for the remainder of the simulation period up to the 100th time step."
}

